n]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 1978]]\n[[Category:Political parties of the Iranian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]\n[[Category:Parties of one-party systems]]\n[[Category:Monarchist parties in Iran]]\n[[Category:Third Position]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n|name            = Resurrection Party of People of Iran\n|logo            = Rastakhiz Party.png\n|logo_size       = 200px\n|caption         = Logo featuring 'Resurrection Party of People of Iran' (center), '[[Persian Constitution of 1906|Constitution]]' (top left), '[[White Revolution|Shah\u2013People Revolution]]' (below), '[[Pahlavi dynasty|Imperial System]]' (top right) writings in Persian\n|founder         = [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]\n|founded         = 2 March 1975 \n|dissolved       = 1 November 1978\n|merger          = [[Iran Novin Party|New Iran Party]] and [[People's Party (Iran)|People's Party]]<ref name=\"AZ\">{{cite book |author=John H. Lorentz|chapter=Rastakhiz Party|title=The A to Z of Iran |volume=209|series=The A to Z Guide Series|publisher=Scarecrow Press|pages=266\u2013268|date=2010|isbn=1461731917}}</ref>\n|headquarters    = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n|membership_year = 1976\n|membership      = 5,000,000<ref name=\"S\">{{cite book|author=Parviz Daneshvar|title=Revolution in Iran|publisher=Springer|page=73|date=2016|isbn=1349140627}}</ref>\n|wing1_title     = Worker wing\n|wing1           = [[Workers' House]]\n|position        = [[Far-right]]\n|ideology        = {{nowrap|[[Iranian nationalism]]<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Bloomsbury|first=Zhand|last=Shakibi|title=Pahlavi Iran and the Politics of Occidentalism|year=2019}}</ref><br>[[National conservatism]]<ref>{{cite book|page=243|year=2018|title=Both Eastern and Western|publisher=CUP|first=Afshin|last=Matin-Asgard}}</ref><br>[[Monarchism]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Daryaee|first=Touraj |author-link=Touraj Daryaee|year=2012|series=Oxford Handbooks in History|title=The Oxford Handbook of Iranian History|isbn=0199732159|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=361}}</ref><br>[[Right-wing populism]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|authorlink=Ervand Abrahamian|title=Tortured Confessions: Prisons and Public Recantations in Modern Iran|year=1999|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|isbn=9780520216235|page=113}}</ref><br>[[Secularism]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|authorlink=Ervand Abrahamian|title=A History of Modern Iran|year=2008|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0521528917|page=153}}</ref><br>[[Democratic centralism]]<ref name=\"A8\">{{cite book|author=Gholam Reza Afkhami|title=The Life and Times of the Shah|date=2008|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|isbn=978-0-520-25328-5|pages=434\u2013444|quote=The conception of the party, a hybrid of the Italian and Spanish schools of fascism, met with widespread opposition and was withdrawn once the queen sided with its opponents. But then fascism yielded to communism. The organization became principle democratic centralism, though the term was not mentioned.}}</ref><ref name=\"PBCP\"/><br>[[Third Position]]<ref name=\"PBCP\"/><br>'''Internal factions''':<ref name=\"AZ\"/><ref name=\"S\"/><br>{{\u2022}}Progressives<br>{{\u2022}}Constructive liberals}}\n|country         = Iran\n|flag           = Flag of Iran (1964).svg\n}}\n'''Rastakhiz Party of People of Iran''' ({{lang-fa|\u062d\u0632\u0628 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0627\u062e\u06cc\u0632 \u0645\u0644\u062a \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646}}) or simply '''Rastakhiz Party''' ({{lang-fa|\u062d\u0632\u0628 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0627\u062e\u06cc\u0632|\u1e24ezb-e Rast\u0101\u1e35iz|lit=Resurgence Party}})<ref name=\"PBCP\"/> was Iran's [[single party|single]] legal political party from 1975 to the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979, founded by the [[Shah]] [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]].<ref name=\"AZ\"/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:P hrastakhiz 7.jpg|thumb|left|Congress of Party]]\nFounded under the government of Prime Minister [[Amir Abbas Hoveyda]], the party has been blamed by some with contributing to the overthrow of the Pahlavi monarchy by antagonizing formerly apolitical Iranians - especially ''[[bazaari]]'' (merchants of the ''[[bazaar]]s'' who, even today, refuse to pay taxes) - with its compulsory membership and dues (taxes), and general interference in the political, economic, and religious concerns of people's lives.<ref name=\"PBCP\">{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|author-link=Ervand Abrahamian|year=1982|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|isbn=0-691-10134-5|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/442 442\u2013446]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/442}}</ref>\nEstablished along with the party was a youth wing\u2014''Rastakhiz Youth''\u2014which Hoveyda referred to as \"the instrument of Iran's development\". Through this youth wing and a special task force of the party, Rastakhiz embarked upon a large-scale anti-[[profiteering (business)|profiteering]] campaign directed against the ''bazaari'' merchants, who were soon identified as \"enemies of the state\". They often lied about Jewish persecution, which is backed up to be lies in government files. In October 1975, the Shah, referring to this campaign as a \"cultural movement\", decreed that anti-profiteerism be made the fourteenth principle of the [[White Revolution]].\n\nThe single party system ended in late 1978 as the [[Iranian Revolution]] gained ground.<ref>Middle Eastern Studies, '''38''' (1), 1  January 2002, pp. 131 - 168</ref>\n\n=== Electoral history ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Election\n!Party leader\n![[Parliament of Iran|Parliament]]\n![[Senate of Iran|Senate]]\n!Ref\n|-\n|[[1975 Iranian legislative election|1975]]\n|[[Amir-Abbas Hoveyda]]\n|{{composition bar|268|268|hex=grey}}\n|{{Composition bar|30|30|hex=grey}}\n|[http://www.sssup.it/UploadDocs/4531_11_Elections_1975_IPU_07.pdf IPU]\n|}\n\n=== Leadership ===\n{{Col-begin}}{{Col-break}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:100%; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n|+ Secretary-Generals\n!Name\n!Tenure\n!Ref\n|-\n||[[Amir-Abbas Hoveyda]]\n||1975\u20131976\n||\n|-\n||[[Jamshid Amouzegar]]\n||1976\u20131977\n||\n|-\n||[[Mohammad Baheri]]\n||1977\u20131978\n||\n|-\n||[[Jamshid Amouzegar]]\n||1978\n||<ref name=\"Saeed\"/>\n|-\n||[[Javad Saeed]]\n||1978\n||<ref name=\"Saeed\">{{citation|date=1979|journal=[[MEED]]|publisher=Economic East Economic Digest Ltd|volume=23|page=17|author=Elizabeth Collard|title=Iran}}</ref>\n|}\n{{Col-break}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:100%; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n|+ Deputy Secretary-Generals\n!Name\n!Tenure\n!Ref\n|-\n||[[Fereydoun Mahdavi]]\n||1975\u20131976\n||<ref>{{cite book|last1=Milani|first1=Abbas|title=Eminent Persians: The Men and Women who Made Modern Iran, 1941-1979|volume=1|date=2008|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse, N.Y.|isbn=978-0815609070|pages=205\u2013212}}</ref>\n|-\n||[[Mohammad Reza Ameli Tehrani]]\n||1976\u20131977 \n||\n|-\n||[[Dariush Homayoon]]\n||1977\u20131978 \n||\n|-\n||[[Javad Saeed]]\n||1978\n||<ref name=\"Saeed\"/>\n|}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Amini, P., [http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a714004438~frm=titlelink?words=rastakhiz|party&hash=2421640627  \"A Single Party State in Iran, 1975-78]: The Rastakhiz Party - the Final Attempt by the Shah to Consolidate his Political Base,\" (not free online),   ''Middle Eastern Studies'', '''38''' (1) January 2002, pp.&nbsp;131 - 168.\n{{commons cat|Rastakhiz Party}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[Ruling party]] of [[Iran]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Iran Novin Party|New Iran Party]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Resurgence Party|years=1975\u20131978}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Islamic Republican Party]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Iran defunct parties}}\n\n[[Category:Banned 