{"title_page": "My Favorite Things (John Coltrane album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = My Favorite Things\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[John Coltrane]]\n| cover      = My_Favorite_Things.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1960\n| recorded   = October 21, 24, 26, 1960\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Modal jazz]]\n| length     = 40:42\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Nesuhi Erteg\u00fcn]]\n| prev_title = [[Coltrane's Sound]]\n| prev_year  = 1960\n| next_title = [[Africa/Brass]]\n| next_year  = 1961\n}}\n{{album ratings\n|rev1 =[[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r136936}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[The Penguin Guide to Jazz]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Penguin\">{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Richard|authorlink1=Richard Cook (journalist)|last2=Morton|first2=Brian|authorlink2=Brian Morton (Scottish writer)|year=2008|title=The Penguin Guide to Jazz Recordings|edition=9th|publisher=[[Penguin Books|Penguin]]|page=286|isbn=978-0-141-03401-0}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=RSJRG>{{Cite book\n |editor-last=Swenson\n |editor-first=J.\n | author-link = \n | year = 1985\n | title = The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide\n | publisher = Random House/Rolling Stone\n | location = USA\n | isbn = 0-394-72643-X\n | pages = 47\n}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Tom Hull (critic)|Tom Hull]]\n|rev4Score = A\u2013<ref>{{cite web|last=Hull|first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Hull (critic)|date=n.d.|url=http://www.tomhull.com/ocston/nm/jazz-40s.html|title=Jazz (1940s-50s)|website=tomhull.com|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''My Favorite Things''''' is the seventh studio album by [[jazz]] musician [[John Coltrane]], released in 1960 on [[Atlantic Records]], catalogue SD-1361. It was the first album to feature Coltrane playing [[soprano saxophone]]. An edited version of [[My Favorite Things (song)|the title track]] became a hit [[single (music)|single]] that gained popularity in 1961 on radio.<ref>Ben Ratliff. ''Coltrane: The Story of A Sound''. New York: Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-374-12606-3}}, p. 60.</ref> The record became a major commercial success. In 1998, the album received the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] award.<ref>[http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#m Grammy Hall of Fame website retrieved 7 August 2011]</ref> It attained gold record status in 2018, having sold 500,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first=|date=January 2019 |title=What's News |publisher= |url= |magazine=[[The New York City Jazz Record]] |volume= |issue=202 |page=5 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 it was voted number 392 in [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|author=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=148}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn March 1960, while on tour in Europe, [[Miles Davis]] purchased a soprano saxophone for Coltrane. With the exception of [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], the instrument had become rare in jazz.<ref>{{cite book| last=Porter| first=Lewis| title=John Coltrane: His Life and Music| publisher=University of Michigan Press| isbn=978-0472086436|pages=181}}</ref> Intrigued by its capabilities, Coltrane began playing it at his summer club dates.<ref>Miles Davis with Quincy Troupe. ''Miles: The Autobiography.'' New York: Simon and Schuster, 1989. {{ISBN|0-671-63504-2}}, pp. 223-224.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the Davis band, Coltrane, for his first regular bookings at New York's Jazz Gallery in the summer of 1960, assembled the first version of the John Coltrane Quartet. The lineup settled by autumn with [[McCoy Tyner]] on piano, [[Steve Davis (bassist)|Steve Davis]] on bass, and [[Elvin Jones]] on drums.<ref>[[Lewis Porter]]. ''John Coltrane: His Life and Music''. [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]]: The University of Michigan Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-472-10161-7}}, pp. 171-180.</ref> Sessions the week before [[Halloween]] at [[Atlantic Studios]] yielded the track \"Village Blues\" for ''[[Coltrane Jazz]]'' and the entirety of this album along with the tracks that Atlantic later assembled into ''[[Coltrane Plays the Blues]]'' and ''[[Coltrane's Sound]]''.\n\n==Music==\nThe title track is a modal rendition of the [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] song \"My Favorite Things\" from ''[[The Sound of Music]]''. The melody is heard numerous times throughout, but instead of playing solos over the written [[chord changes]], both Tyner and Coltrane take extended solos over [[Vamp (music)|vamps]] of the two [[tonic (music)|tonic]] chords, [[E minor]] and [[E major]], played in [[waltz time]].<ref>Porter, pp. 182-183.</ref> In the documentary ''[[The World According to John Coltrane]]'', narrator Ed Wheeler remarks on the impact that this song's popularity had on Coltrane's career:\n<blockquote>In 1960, Coltrane left Miles [Davis] and formed his own quartet to further explore modal playing, freer directions, and a growing Indian influence. They transformed \"My Favorite Things\", the cheerful populist song from 'The Sound of Music,' into a hypnotic eastern [[dervish]] dance. The recording was a hit and became Coltrane's most requested tune\u2014and a bridge to broad public acceptance.</blockquote>\n\nOn March 3, 1998, [[Rhino Records]] reissued ''My Favorite Things'' as part of its Atlantic 50th Anniversary Jazz Gallery series. Included as [[bonus tracks]] were both sides of the \"My Favorite Things\" single, released as Atlantic 5012 in 1961.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| title1          = [[My Favorite Things (song)|My Favorite Things]]\n| writer1         = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]],<br>[[Richard Rodgers]]\n| length1         = 13:41\n| title2          = [[Ev'ry Time We Say Goodbye]]\n| writer2         = [[Cole Porter]]\n| length2         = 5:39\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title1          = [[Summertime (George Gershwin song)|Summertime]]\n| writer1         = [[Ira Gershwin]], [[DuBose Heyward]], [[George Gershwin]]\n| length1         = 11:31\n| title2          = [[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\n| writer2         = Ira Gershwin, George Gershwin\n| length2         = 9:34\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 1998 reissue bonus tracks\n| title5          = My Favorite Things, Part 1\n| note5           = single [[A-side and B-side|A-side]]\n| writer5         = [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]\n| length5         = 2:45\n| title6          = My Favorite Things, Part 2\n| note6           = single B-side\n| writer6         = Rodgers and Hammerstein\n| length6         = 3:02\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[John Coltrane]] \u2013 [[soprano saxophone]] <small>on side one and bonus tracks</small>; [[tenor saxophone]] <small>on side two</small>\n* [[McCoy Tyner]] \u2013 [[piano]]\n* [[Steve Davis (bassist)|Steve Davis]] \u2013 [[double bass]]\n* [[Elvin Jones]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n===Production personnel===\n* [[Nesuhi Erteg\u00fcn]] \u2014 [[record producer|production]]\n* [[Tom Dowd]], Phil Iehle \u2014 [[audio engineering|engineering]]\n* [[Lee Friedlander]] \u2014 photography\n* Loring Eutemey \u2014 [[record sleeve|cover design]]\n* Bill Coss \u2014 [[liner notes]]\n* Bob Carlton, Patrick Milligan \u2014 reissue supervision\n* Bill Inglot, Dan Hersch \u2014 [[audio mastering|digital remastering]]\n* Rachel Gutek \u2014 reissue design\n* Hugh Brown \u2014 reissue [[art direction]]\n* [[Nat Hentoff]] \u2014 reissue liner notes\n* Steven Chean \u2014 reissue editorial supervision\n* Ted Myers, Elizabeth Pavone \u2014 reissue editorial coordination\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=John Coltrane|title=My Favorite Things|award=Gold|certyear=2018|relyear=1961}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://room34.com/coltrane/thesis/ \"John Coltrane, Avant Garde Jazz, and the Evolution of \"My Favorite Things\"] &mdash; A [[thesis]] paper with musical analysis\n*[http://shawllobree.wordpress.com/2010/10/20/my-favorite-things-the-50th-anniversary-of-john-coltranes-landmark-recording-sessions/ \"My Favorite Things, The 50th Anniversary of John Coltrane's Landmark Recording Sessions\"]\n*[https://beta.prx.org/stories/53808-my-favorite-things-at-50 \"My Favorite Things at 50,\"] radio documentary on the 50th anniversary of John Coltrane's rendition of \"My Favorite Things.\"\n\n{{John Coltrane}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:My Favorite Things}}\n[[Category:1960 albums]]\n[[Category:John Coltrane albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nesuhi Ertegun]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Modal jazz albums]]\n[[Category:Instrumental albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = My Favorite Things\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[John Coltrane]]\n| cover      = My_Favorite_Things.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1960\n| recorded   = October 21, 24, 26, 1960\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Modal jazz]]\n| length     = 40:42\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Nesuhi Erteg\u00fcn]]\n| prev_title = [[Coltrane's Sound]]\n| prev_year  = 1960\n| next_title = [[Africa/Brass]]\n| next_year  = 1961\n}}\n{{album ratings\n|rev1 =[[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r136936}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[The Penguin Guide to Jazz]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Penguin\">{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Richard|authorlink1=Richard Cook (journalist)|last2=Morton|first2=Brian|authorlink2=Brian Morton (Scottish writer)|year=2008|title=The Penguin Guide to Jazz Recordings|edition=9th|publisher=[[Penguin Books|Penguin]]|page=286|isbn=978-0-141-03401-0}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=RSJRG>{{Cite book\n |editor-last=Swenson\n |editor-first=J.\n | author-link = \n | year = 1985\n | title = The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide\n | publisher = Random House/Rolling Stone\n | location = USA\n | isbn = 0-394-72643-X\n | pages = 47\n}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Tom Hull (critic)|Tom Hull]]\n|rev4Score = A\u2013<ref>{{cite web|last=Hull|first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Hull (critic)|date=n.d.|url=http://www.tomhull.com/ocston/nm/jazz-40s.html|title=Jazz (1940s-50s)|website=tomhull.com|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''My Favorite Things''''' is the seventh studio album by [[jazz]] musician [[John Coltrane]], released in 1960 on [[Atlantic Records]], catalogue SD-1361. It was the first album to feature Coltrane playing [[soprano saxophone]]. An edited version of [[My Favorite Things (song)|the title track]] became a hit [[single (music)|single]] that gained popularity in 1961 on radio.<ref>Ben Ratliff. ''Coltrane: The Story of A Sound''. New York: Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-374-12606-3}}, p. 60.</ref> The record became a major commercial success. In 1998, the album received the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] award.<ref>[http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#m Grammy Hall of Fame website retrieved 7 August 2011]</ref> It attained gold record status in 2018, having sold 500,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first=|date=January 2019 |title=What's News |publisher= |url= |magazine=[[The New York City Jazz Record]] |volume= |issue=202 |page=5 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 it was voted number 392 in [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|author=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=148}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn March 1960, while on tour in Europe, [[Miles Davis]] purchased a soprano saxophone for Coltrane. With the exception of [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], the instrument had become rare in jazz.<ref>{{cite book| last=Porter| first=Lewis| title=John Coltrane: His Life and Music| publisher=University of Michigan Press| isbn=978-0472086436|pages=181}}</ref> Intrigued by its capabilities, Coltrane began playing it at his summer club dates.<ref>Miles Davis with Quincy Troupe. ''Miles: The Autobiography.'' New York: Simon and Schuster, 1989. {{ISBN|0-671-63504-2}}, pp. 223-224.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the Davis band, Coltrane, for his first regular bookings at New York's Jazz Gallery in the summer of 1960, assembled the first version of the John Coltrane Quartet. The line-up settled by autumn with [[McCoy Tyner]] on piano, [[Steve Davis (bassist)|Steve Davis]] on bass, and [[Elvin Jones]] on drums.<ref>[[Lewis Porter]]. ''John Coltrane: His Life and Music''. [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]]: The University of Michigan Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-472-10161-7}}, pp. 171-180.</ref> Sessions the week before [[Halloween]] at  [[Atlantic Studios]] yielded the track \"Village Blues\" for ''[[Coltrane Jazz]]'' and the entirety of this album along with the tracks that Atlantic would later assemble into ''[[Coltrane Plays the Blues]]'' and ''[[Coltrane's Sound]]''.\n\n==Music==\nThe title track is a modal rendition of the [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]] song \"My Favorite Things\" from ''[[The Sound of Music]]''. The melody is heard numerous times throughout, but instead of playing solos over the written [[chord changes]], both Tyner and Coltrane take extended solos over [[Vamp (music)|vamps]] of the two [[tonic (music)|tonic]] chords, [[E minor]] and [[E major]], played in [[waltz time]].<ref>Porter, pp. 182-183.</ref> In the documentary ''[[The World According to John Coltrane]]'', narrator Ed Wheeler remarks on the impact that this song's popularity had on Coltrane's career:\n<blockquote>In 1960, Coltrane left Miles [Davis] and formed his own quartet to further explore modal playing, freer directions, and a growing Indian influence. They transformed \"My Favorite Things\", the cheerful populist song from 'The Sound of Music,' into a hypnotic eastern [[dervish]] dance. The recording was a hit and became Coltrane's most requested tune\u2014and a bridge to broad public acceptance.</blockquote>\n\nOn March 3, 1998, [[Rhino Records]] reissued ''My Favorite Things'' as part of its Atlantic 50th Anniversary Jazz Gallery series. Included as [[bonus tracks]] were both sides of the \"My Favorite Things\" single, released as Atlantic 5012 in 1961.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| title1          = [[My Favorite Things (song)|My Favorite Things]]\n| writer1         = [[Oscar Hammerstein II]],<br>[[Richard Rodgers]]\n| length1         = 13:41\n| title2          = [[Ev'ry Time We Say Goodbye]]\n| writer2         = [[Cole Porter]]\n| length2         = 5:39\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title1          = [[Summertime (George Gershwin song)|Summertime]]\n| writer1         = [[Ira Gershwin]], [[DuBose Heyward]], [[George Gershwin]]\n| length1         = 11:31\n| title2          = [[But Not for Me (song)|But Not for Me]]\n| writer2         = Ira Gershwin, George Gershwin\n| length2         = 9:34\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 1998 reissue bonus tracks\n| title5          = My Favorite Things, Part 1\n| note5           = single [[A-side and B-side|A-side]]\n| writer5         = [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]\n| length5         = 2:45\n| title6          = My Favorite Things, Part 2\n| note6           = single B-side\n| writer6         = Rodgers and Hammerstein\n| length6         = 3:02\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[John Coltrane]] \u2013 [[soprano saxophone]] <small>on side one and bonus tracks</small>; [[tenor saxophone]] <small>on side two</small>\n* [[McCoy Tyner]] \u2013 [[piano]]\n* [[Steve Davis (bassist)|Steve Davis]] \u2013 [[double bass]]\n* [[Elvin Jones]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n===Production personnel===\n* [[Nesuhi Erteg\u00fcn]] \u2014 [[record producer|production]]\n* [[Tom Dowd]], Phil Iehle \u2014 [[audio engineering|engineering]]\n* [[Lee Friedlander]] \u2014 photography\n* Loring Eutemey \u2014 [[record sleeve|cover design]]\n* Bill Coss \u2014 [[liner notes]]\n* Bob Carlton, Patrick Milligan \u2014 reissue supervision\n* Bill Inglot, Dan Hersch \u2014 [[audio mastering|digital remastering]]\n* Rachel Gutek \u2014 reissue design\n* Hugh Brown \u2014 reissue [[art direction]]\n* [[Nat Hentoff]] \u2014 reissue liner notes\n* Steven Chean \u2014 reissue editorial supervision\n* Ted Myers, Elizabeth Pavone \u2014 reissue editorial coordination\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=John Coltrane|title=My Favorite Things|award=Gold|certyear=2018|relyear=1961}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://room34.com/coltrane/thesis/ \"John Coltrane, Avant Garde Jazz, and the Evolution of \"My Favorite Things\"] &mdash; A [[thesis]] paper with musical analysis\n*[http://shawllobree.wordpress.com/2010/10/20/my-favorite-things-the-50th-anniversary-of-john-coltranes-landmark-recording-sessions/ \"My Favorite Things, The 50th Anniversary of John Coltrane's Landmark Recording Sessions\"]\n*[https://beta.prx.org/stories/53808-my-favorite-things-at-50 \"My Favorite Things at 50,\"] radio documentary on the 50th anniversary of John Coltrane's rendition of \"My Favorite Things.\"\n\n{{John Coltrane}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:My Favorite Things}}\n[[Category:1960 albums]]\n[[Category:John Coltrane albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nesuhi Ertegun]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Modal jazz albums]]\n[[Category:Instrumental albums]]\n", "name_user": "Wukai", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Favorite_Things_(John_Coltrane_album)"}
{"title_page": "IFK Malm\u00f6", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports team\n| name = IFK Malm\u00f6\n| color1 = \n| color2 = \n| logo = IFK Malm\u00f6 logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| alt = \n| caption = IFK Malm\u00f6 logo\n| full_name = Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Malm\u00f6 Sweden\n| nicknames = Di gule, Kanarief\u00e5glarna\n| sport = [[association football]], [[bandy]], [[handball]]\n| founded = {{start date|df=y|1899}}\n| folded = \n| current = \n| league = \n| conference = \n| division = \n| history = \n| arena = \n| ballpark = \n| stadium = [[Malm\u00f6 IP]]\n| city = [[File:Malm\u00f6_fulla_vapen.svg|19px]] [[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden\n| colors = \n| colours = \n| owner = \n| president = \n| coach = \n| manager = \n| gm = \n| championships = \n| conference_titles = \n| division_titles = \n| playoff_berths = \n| anthem = \n| cheerleaders = \n| dancers = \n| mascot = \n| fanclub = \n| broadcasters = \n| media = \n| uniforms = \n| branches = \n| members = \n| blank_label = \n| blank_data = \n| blank_label1 = \n| blank_data1 = \n| blank_label2 = \n| blank_data2 = \n| blank_label3 = \n| blank_data3 = \n| website = https://www.ifkmalmo.se\n}}\n'''Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Kamraterna Malm\u00f6''', more commonly known as '''IFK Malm\u00f6''', is a Swedish [[sports club]] with several departments, located in [[Malm\u00f6]]. The club was founded on 23 April 1899. \n\nThe football department of IFK Malm\u00f6 is one of the oldest [[Association football|football]] clubs in [[Sweden]].\n\n==Departments==\n* [[Bandy]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Bandy]]\n* [[Association football]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Fotboll]]\n* [[Handball]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Handboll]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.ifkmalmo.se}}\n* [http://www.ifkmalmosupport.com IFK Malm\u00f6 fans website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:IFK Malmo}}\n[[Category:Sport in Malm\u00f6]]\n[[Category:Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Kamraterna|Malmo ifk]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports team\n| name              = IFK Malm\u00f6\n| color1            = \n| color2            = \n| logo              = IFK Malm\u00f6 logo.svg\n| logo_size         = 200px\n| alt               =\n| caption           = IFK Malm\u00f6 logo\n| full_name         = Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Malm\u00f6 Sweden\n| nicknames         = Di gule, Kanarief\u00e5glarna\n| sport             = [[association football]], [[bandy]], [[handball]]\n| founded           = {{start date|df=y|1899}}\n| folded            =\n| current           = \n| league            = \n| conference        =\n| division          =\n| history           = \n| arena             = \n| ballpark          = \n| stadium           = [[Malm\u00f6 IP]]\n| city              = [[File:Malm\u00f6_fulla_vapen.svg|19px]] [[Malm\u00f6]], {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Sweden]]\n| colors            = \n| colours           = \n| owner             = \n| president         =\n| coach             = \n| manager           = \n| gm                =\n| championships     = \n| conference_titles =\n| division_titles   = \n| playoff_berths    =\n| anthem            =\n| cheerleaders      = \n| dancers           = \n| mascot            = \n| fanclub           =\n| broadcasters      = \n| media             = \n| uniforms          =\n| branches          =\n| members           =\n| blank_label       = \n| blank_data        = \n| blank_label1      = \n| blank_data1       = \n| blank_label2      = \n| blank_data2       = \n| blank_label3      = \n| blank_data3       = \n| website           = \n}}\n'''Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Kamraterna Malm\u00f6''', more commonly known as '''IFK Malm\u00f6''', is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[sports club]] with several departments, located in [[Malm\u00f6]]. The club was founded on 23 April 1899. \n\nThe football department of IFK Malm\u00f6 is one of the oldest [[Association football|football]] clubs in [[Sweden]].\n\n==Departments==\n* [[Bandy]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Bandy]]\n* [[Association football]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Fotboll]]\n* [[Handball]], see [[IFK Malm\u00f6 Handboll]]\n\n==